{"title":"What I’ve been reading","link":"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/904341014/0/marginalrevolution~What-Ive-been-reading.html","date":1725944886000,"content":"<p>1. Bécquer Seguín, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Op-Ed-Novel-Literary-History-Post-Franco/dp/0674260104/ref=sr_1_1?crid=291REUPPIM0Z9&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.gUcOnLpH53cI19zl6MJvvg.Tt5AIheDypJl1iy5IYO0bx4Ti-Z4JiTrzVii5x2iRGY&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=The+Op-Ed+Novel%3A+A+Literary+History+of+Post-Franco+Spain&amp;qid=1725830064&amp;sprefix=the+op-ed+novel+a+literary+history+of+post-franco+spain%2Caps%2C111&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">The Op-Ed Novel: A Literary History of Post-Franco Spain</a>.  I liked this book very much, as it gave me extremely useful background on the Spanish fiction I enjoy.  It may make less sense to read if you don’t already know the relevant fiction, but in any case a fine work.  Imagine, by the way, if America had an equally strong correlation between novelists and Op-Ed columnists.</p>\r\n<p>2. Ken McNab, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Shake-Up-Baby-Beatlemania-Mayhem/dp/163936658X/ref=sr_1_1?crid=BXGTM0PZTDPD&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.XEBsvmhYP9hzd7lwA0iX7g.XXmk9bo4eH-5nKIxwZRfGmPHFaMAnkVWx2UqHfLA8VA&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=Shake+It+Up%2C+Baby%21+The+Rise+of+Beatlemania+and+the+Mayhem+of+1963&amp;qid=1725829997&amp;sprefix=shake+it+up%2C+baby+the+rise+of+beatlemania+and+the+mayhem+of+1963%2Caps%2C98&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">Shake It Up, Baby! The Rise of Beatlemania and the Mayhem of 1963</a>.  At the beginning of that year, John and Paul despaired of making it as a rock band, and expected to end up as songwriters for other people, much like Goffin-King at the time.  By the end of the year however…  This is the story of how that happened.  Very well done.</p>\r\n<p>3. Ian Frazier, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Paradise-Bronx-Times-Greatest-Borough/dp/0374280568/ref=sr_1_1?crid=NNHI09XZUQNR&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.pC8zAZFugkgcz0hRwrHq44xcbx3HBprDQaQ1DvxECDr_Ib-zbmRq0pTbUG67iJZy.FCdOrIjGgzG9fnd0Nlgyjc0x6mMQvKvZYiO5Se5YdH8&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=Paradise+Bronx%3A+The+Life+and+Times+of+New+York%27s+Greatest+Borough&amp;qid=1725829939&amp;sprefix=paradise+bronx+the+life+and+times+of+new+york%27s+greatest+borough%2Caps%2C88&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">Paradise Bronx: The Life and Times of New York’s Greatest Borough</a>.  An excellent, fun, and much-needed book.  I liked the parts about the 20th century best.  I am still longing for that cost-benefit analysis of the Cross-Bronx Expressway, though.  We know the Interstate Highway system passes the cost-benefit test massively, but do all of its constituent parts?</p>\r\n<p>4. Simon Morrison, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Tchaikovskys-Empire-Russias-Greatest-Composer/dp/030019210X/ref=sr_1_1?crid=AL6XY3EL4CRM&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.Egu2dr7Qr0UwnCwHSTyytQ.56suYnQZxhkDb_ID65hJfUCO_9G0gUPOS3j0ISPM6mM&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=Tchaikovsky%27s+Empire%3A+A+New+Life+of+Russia%27s+Greatest+Composer&amp;qid=1725829891&amp;sprefix=tchaikovsky%27s+empire+a+new+life+of+russia%27s+greatest+composer%2Caps%2C90&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">Tchaikovsky’s Empire: A New Life of Russia’s Greatest Composer</a>.  My favorite book about Tchaikovsky, engaging but it also covers the music for the music’s sake as well.  I liked this sentence from the book jacket: “His life and art were framed by Russian national ambition, and his work was the emanation of an imperial subject: kaleidoscopic, capacious, cosmopolitan.”  The book does go relatively light on Tchaikovsky’s um…personal life.</p>\r\n<p>There is Matt Grossman and David A. Hopkins, and their suitably titled and subtitled<a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Polarized-Degrees-Transformed-American-Politics/dp/1316512010/ref=sr_1_1?crid=3BLTL8NPSJF52&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.VQcoC-OiFUcvIg-ytbllAA._B8S-jQP04uSvjkkmMTvoEFMLRWrqchTyDDilYwNYHw&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=Polarized+Degrees%3A+How+the+Diploma+Divide+and+the+Culture+War+Transformed+American+Politics&amp;qid=1725829656&amp;sprefix=polarized+degrees+how+the+diploma+divide+and+the+culture+war+transformed+american+politics%2Caps%2C95&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\"> Polarized Degrees: How the Diploma Divide and the Culture War Transformed American Politics</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Pakistan is a drastically undercovered country, but now Lahore has some coverage, in Manan Ahmed Asif’s <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Disrupted-City-Walking-Pathways-History-ebook/dp/B0CFWQD1XL/ref=sr_1_1?crid=2XDVQJQSWO3YH&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.aiXm1iHatRs3xsEicGbHzQ.IPiK3i3d_TCrvhcbmKdLiZUwoe2ttEQKSl0KZ14ivag&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=Disrupted+City%3A+Walking+the+Pathways+of+Memory+and+History+in+Lahore&amp;qid=1725829621&amp;sprefix=disrupted+city+walking+the+pathways+of+memory+and+history+in+lahore%2Caps%2C101&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">Disrupted City: Walking the Pathways of Memory and History in Lahore</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Marieke Brandt, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Tribes-Politics-Yemen-History-Conflict/dp/0197783252/ref=sr_1_1?crid=1SHW3Q9UQ41DZ&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.qjE5p4q1PGjYjrn19u7YkcPQSjyb27tdoFUqxstN4yg.4D_6E0BzWHdBhoeui-AyKwVV9PBGvVOgD1kaqpZdYW8&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=Tribes+and+Politics+in+Yemen%3A+A+History+of+the+Houthi+Conflict&amp;qid=1725829567&amp;sprefix=tribes+and+politics+in+yemen+a+history+of+the+houthi+conflict%2Caps%2C105&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">Tribes and Politics in Yemen: A History of the Houthi Conflict</a> had far more detailed than I was seeking.  But I read about one fifth of it, and learned a great deal from that.</p>\r\n<p>J.C.D. Clark, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Enlightenment-Idea-Its-History/dp/0198916280/ref=sr_1_1?crid=18OM4KSM5HWTG&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.4SnLXy0e1jQqDz3ItfB-qfC3eWkhBkhHt7Jt5goEWOwOpd9wgs-71sQODPHDHQf1mNxa_BIu2KSRrwiKt5ThszA7yDiqIu3ZlLSiFSzLcU5vNUy3sDpm3Wu8sFOolXY8vvXw4CkBOsyfxT14MZkcXcgV8b7BGEtkvQxD_cb0h5FQhjuPsc5saOMvtoULX3I6BI-seEh7zYXWsmtboAjNJLjsddrmPs807nc6GuwtevI.FZmJx_o0CvgblX3wc188rB7HV1X3d-I_LYxVk5HTfa4&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=The+Enlightenment%3A+An+Idea+and+its+History&amp;qid=1725829535&amp;sprefix=the+enlightenment+an+idea+and+its+history%2Caps%2C102&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">The Enlightenment: An Idea and its History</a>, sounds smart but somehow stays too much at the meta-level of commentary on the commentary?</p>\r\n<p>Victor Davis Hanson has a new book <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/End-Everything-Wars-Descend-Annihilation/dp/1541673522/ref=sr_1_1?crid=3QULYLY7EZX9I&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.BRI6MUrn77iqONJdlPsZ0HTbRhYpwvRfny0M5sqTfocTnq11cMXKOyVTAAvooboEXb--FiHE3q5fsRuxDQTH4JiVn6s0R0tHP5klRWKVt7c.Nl_lFf6u0CjqYxUH04mFipeucT8Z23fhD7KLgNz4cok&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=The+End+of+Everything%3A+How+Wars+Descend+into+Annihilation&amp;qid=1725829495&amp;sprefix=the+end+of+everything+how+wars+descend+into+annihilation%2Caps%2C65&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">The End of Everything: How Wars Descend into Annihilation</a>.</p>\r\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/2024/09/what-ive-been-reading-259.html\">What I’ve been reading</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://marginalrevolution.com\">Marginal REVOLUTION</a>.</p>\r\n<img height=\"1\" width=\"1\" src=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/i/904341014/0/marginalrevolution\" />\r\n<div><a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/_/28/904341014/marginalrevolution\"><img hei